Participant presented to ER after a fall on 07/19/2017. Participant stated she was on the phone with her son when she felt dizzy and fell down. Her son confirmed that he heard her fall. There was no loss of bowel or bladder and no loss of consciousness. There was no chest pain or shortness of breath. She hit her head when she fell and hit it a few additional times trying to get up. She was unable to get off the floor herself. She stated she does not normally fall. She lives at home alone in a 2 story house & goes up/down the stairs without difficulty. She has a walker but rarely uses it. After being admitted to the hospital, her work up came back negative. She had dizziness when she sat up. Her EKG showed inferolateral ST depressions. Her CT C-spine showed no acute spine fracture & CT of the head was negative. She was given gentle IVF hydration. She was alert and oriented x3. She was discharged on 07/20/2017 to a nearby nursing unit. She was told she cannot return home and needs skilled nursing. She was counseled about using her walker. Her son agreed with this and was referred to multiple agencies for help with this process.
AEOTHERHX: See narrative above. Participant has a history of falls and dizziness leading back to 2011. Although she has a walker, she rarely uses it. Because of the severity of this fall, the participant was discharged to a skilled nursing unit. She was told she cannot return home and needs skilled nursing and 24-hour care from now on. Her son agreed with this and was referred to multiple agencies for help with this process.

AEHEVNT: Multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular and ductal carcinoma, left breast
AEHCOMM: Participant’s mammogram on 07/12/2017 showed a small 6 MM speculated density in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. She had a left lateral biopsy on her breast on 07/20/2017 and was diagnosed with recurrent invasive carcinoma, ER/PR positive and HER-2 negative by FISH. She was treated surgically with left breast wide local excision on 08/01/2017. Pathology showed multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular (85%) and ductal (15%) carcinoma, Nottingham Grade 3 (score 2 for tubule formation, 3 for nuclear atypia, and 3 for mitosis). DCIS is present. No necrosis of the invasive carcinoma was identified and it measured 2.6 X 2.6 X 3.0 CM. The participant had a left breast re-excision on 08/22/2017 which showed two foci of residual invasive mixed mammary carcinoma (largest focus measuring 12 MM) with 1 MM focal positive margin. Her oncologist prescribed her Anastrozole 1mg QD PO. More oncology records have been requested.

DERR 13 Feb 2018. SAE = Hospitalization. Participant experienced swelling in left hand and arm, lacy rash on right side of body, and increased lethargy on 05 Feb 2018. Caregiver (spouse) and nursing home staff made the decision to bring participant to the ER on 06 Feb 2018. She was admitted to the ER for extended stay observation. Workup for infection was negative. She was treated with antibiotics (vancomysin/zosyn)* for one day, and was observed for 24 hours after antibiotics were discontinued. PT, OT, and Neurology consults were conducted but led to no new diagnoses. Neuro consult recommended to taper off lorazepam. Morning dose decreased 1mg to 0.5mg. Evening dose decreased 2mg to 1mg. Suggested to maintain lower dose for 2 more weeks then discontinue. Use as PRN for agitation. No other changes were made to her con med list. Participant was discharged on 08 Feb 2018 and returned to her nursing care facility. No diagnoses were given for swelling, rash, and lethargy. Symptoms were resolved at time of discharge, and health was considered back to baseline.
*vanc 1500 Q24Hr (given a 2g load prior) and zosyn 3.375g IV piggy back Q6Hr run at 100mL/Hr infuse over 30 min [per EMR documentation]

AEOTHERHX: DMS 6/24/19 - Subject with PMH of GERD , HTN, hyperlipodemia presented to local ER with complaints of acute nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain. Pain began 2300 on 4/12/19. Initially attributed to "food poisoning"  but when pain persisted presented to ER. CT abdominal scan showed partial small bowel obstruction.  On exam epigastic and RUQ tenderness present. General surgery was contacted to place a nasogasrtric (NG) tube.  Prior to ER, at home had several episodes of nonbloody no bilious emesis. Had normal bowel movement about one hour after pain began. Was admitted for continued NG tube decompression and IV fluids.  By4/14/19 subject was passing flatus, denied nausea, emesis. NG tube with 1375 ml gastric content. Labs revealed no leukocytosis . H & H stable, electrolytes WNL. No evidence of acute kidney injury. NGT removed and started on clear liquids. Recieved pantoprazole IV for GERD while admitted and had prn zofran IV ordered. By 4/15/19 subject continued to improve. Felt well after breakfast. Labs and vitals were normal subject was discharged home.

After sleeping in, both caregiver, daughter, and participant went straight in to take shower together around 12:30 PM. After several minutes, in hot shower, participant complained of dizziness and fainted. Daughter caught her and lowered her down. Eyes were open, breathing normally, but unresponsive for about two minutes. Afterward, participant got up and was back to her baseline. Resumed usual activities and behavior for remainder of day. And since then, no recurrences. Given that participant was "back to normal" so quickly. Family did not seek medical attention. At the time: no slurred speech, no facial droop, no extremity weakness, numbness, or tingling. No chest pain or palpitations. No dyspnea. No recent illness. No fever or chills. No seizures. 
OF NOTE: Participant's usual routine is to get up between 6AM and 8AM and eat breakfast around 8 AM. On the day of the event, participant was drowsy and had not eaten or drank anything prior to taking a hot shower. This suggests vasovagal syncope.

GI bleed with associated coffee ground emesis, leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactic acidosis, myoglobinemia, diarrhea, resulting in patient's death.
AEOTHERHX: Patient began having coffee ground emesis during the evening of 6 June 2020.  Nursing home sent patient to emergency room and she was admitted to the hospital on 7 June 2020.  She was initially noted to be hypotensive with blood pressure of 70/37.  Lab work showed multiple derangements including leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactate 5.4 mmol/L, and myoglobin > 24,000.  She had non-bloody foul-smelling diarrhea.  She was given IV bolus fluids and had improvement in blood pressure.  Diagnosis was GI bleed due to suspected significant intra-abdominal pathology with main concern for ischemic bowel.  Lengthy discussion was had with patient's son/healthcare proxy who is at the bedside.  Due to patient's and sons wishes, decision was made to forego aggressive workup or management.  She was transitioned to comfort care measures including around the clock and as needed analgesia with Dilaudid, Ativan for restlessness, and Haldol for agitation.  Patient expired at 4:40 on 8 jun 2020.  Son called site at 8:38 on 8 Jun 2020 to report.
